INTRODUCTION

Police departments and government officials seek to predict crime rates so that they are better equipped to combat that crime and more efficiently allocate personnel and resources.
In order to ensure accurate predictions, it is important to ensure that we have high quality data1 and that we are using appropriate models.
This study endeavors to predict per capita crime rate in the Boston area. To ensure we have the highest quality prediction, I considered linear regression with variables selected via best subset selection, ridge regression, and lasso regression.
After creating the models and testing them, the linear regression model has a Mean Standard Error (MSE) of 94.47, the ridge regression model had a MSE of 0.64, and the lasso model has a MSE of 0.67. Because the MSE values are nearly identical, I would be confident using either the ridge regression model or the lasso model to predict per capita crime rate.

DATA

The data for this study was obtained from the Boston dataset in the MASS library. The variables are broken down as follows:

CRIM - per capita crime rate by town

ZN - proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 square feet

INDUS - proportion of non-retail business acres per town

CHAS - Charles River dummy variable (1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)

NOX - nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)

RM - average number of rooms per dwelling

AGE - proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940

DIS - weighted distances to five Boston employment centres

RAD - index of accessibility to radial highways

TAX - full-value property-tax rate per $10,000

PTRATIO - pupil-teacher ratio by town

BLACK - 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town

LSTAT - % lower status of the population

MEDV - Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s

To ensure an accurate prediction, it is essential that we are using complete, quality data. So, we will first examine the data. A complete summary of the variables can be found in Figure 1. Checking for incomplete data also reveals that we have a complete data set.

Now, I will take a closer look at the relationships between the data points. If I want to compare linear regression, ridge regression, and the lasso I will need to first set up a linear regression as seen below:

linear.boston <- lm(
  crim ~  zn + indus + chas + nox + rm + age + dis + rad + tax + ptratio + black
  + lstat + medv, data = Boston
  )

Ill first take a look at scatterplots of the relationships between per capita crime rate and each of the predictors:

It doesnt look like I have very good linear relationships between per capita crime and many of the predictors, so a transformation will be in order. Before, I move on, here are the plots of the residuals:

These residual plots show we have some pretty clear violations of the assumptions of linear regression. In the Residuals vs.Fits plot, you can see that the points do not bounce and down nicely around the zero value indicating that they fail to meet the assumption of a linear relationship. Additionally, the points spread out more as you move on down the line indicating that they fail to meet the assumption of equal variance. Looking at the Normal Q-Q plot, the points fail to follow the dashed line, indicating that the residuals fail to meet the assumption of being from a normal distribution.

To rectify this, I will first explore take a log transformation of the predictors. I have taking the log transformation of ( zn + 1) because of the zeroes in this variable. I chose not to take a log transformation of chas because it is a dummy variable coded with 0 and 1.

Here is the model:

linear.boston.1 <- lm(
  crim ~  log(zn + 1) + log(indus) + chas + log(nox) + log(rm) + log(age) + log(dis) 
  + log(rad) + log(tax) + log(ptratio) + log(black) + log(lstat) + log(medv), data = Boston
  )

And here is a plot of the relationships between per capita crime and the predictors:

These linear relationships look very slightly better but not significantly so.
Before trying another transformation, lets check out the residuals:



There definitely still appear to be violations of the assumptions of linear models. In the Residuals vs. Fits plot, you can see that the points do not bounce and down nicely around the zero value indicating that they fail to meet the assumption of a linear relationship.  Additionally, the points spread out more as you move on down the line indicating that they fail to meet the assumption of equal variance.
Looking at the Normal Q-Q plot, the points fail to follow the dashed line, indicating that the residuals fail to meet the assumption of being from a normal distribution. 
Next, I'll try transforming per capita crime by taking the natural log of the predictor _crim_ and leaving the predictors as they are:


```r
linear.log.boston <- lm(log(crim) ~  zn + indus + chas + nox + rm + age + dis + rad + tax + ptratio + black + lstat + medv, data = Boston)

First, the scatterplots showing the relationships between crim and the various predictors:

The linear relationships in these plots look significantly better than our previous transformations. To confirm this transformation, we will take a look at our resiudal plots:

The residual plots also look significiantly better. In the Residuals vs Fitted plot,the points now appear to center around the zero line indicating a linear relationship. The points also appear to maintain a roughly equal distance from that zero line, indicating equal variance. Looking at the Normal Q-Q plot, the points roughly follow the dashed line indicating that the residuals are normally distributed.

The next issue to consider is multicollinearity. The first step I will take for this is looking at a visual representation of the correlation between the variables:

library(corrplot)
## Warning: package 'corrplot' was built under R version 3.6.3
## corrplot 0.84 loaded
corr.Boston <- cor(Boston)
corrplot(corr.Boston)

It definitely appears that there are strong correlations between some of the variables. To get a more specific idea of what we are dealing with, I will examine the Variance Inflation Factors (VIF) from the model:

library(car)
vif(linear.log.boston)
##       zn    indus     chas      nox       rm      age      dis      rad 
## 2.325094 3.987753 1.094326 4.551563 2.258113 3.100801 4.289041 7.158834 
##      tax  ptratio    black    lstat     medv 
## 9.195495 1.984489 1.369741 3.561476 3.772856

A VIF of 1 indicates no correlation. A VIF between 1 and 5 indicates moderate correlation and a VIF greater than 5 indicates significant correlation. It looks like most of our predictors indicate moderate to significant correlation.

However this is not necessarily a problem. Accoring to Applied Linear Statistical Models, 4th Edition: The fact that some or all predictor variables are correlated among themselves does not, in general, inhibit our ability to obtain a good fit nor does it tend to affect inferences about mean responses or predictions of new observations.
" Fortunately, can still use a model with multicollinearity to predict new responses, we just have to be careful about using that model to make inferences about the impact of any particular predictor.

Since the goal of this study is to predict per capita crime rate, I will not try to correct for the multicollinearity.

Now that I have made the necessary transformation, I will set up a matrix with our variables to predict crime rate and our response vector and we can move on to analyzing potential models:

Boston.pred = model.matrix(crim ~ ., Boston )[,-1]
Boston.resp = log(Boston$crim)

ANALYSES

We now move on to generating the models for comparison. First, I will determine the best linear regression from this data set based on best subset selection. Here I fit the best subsets model:

library (leaps)
regfit.full=regsubsets(log(crim) ~ ., Boston, nvmax = 13)
reg.summary <- summary(regfit.full)

The full breakdown of models is provided in Figure 2.

I know have my best subset selection. To find the best model from each of these best models, I will now set up my training and test sets:

set.seed (1)
train=sample (c(TRUE ,FALSE), nrow(Boston),rep=TRUE)
test =(!train )

The next step is to apply regsubsets() to the training set to perform best subset selection:

regfit.best=regsubsets (log(crim) ~.,data = Boston[train ,],
nvmax =13)

We can now make a model matrix from the test data:

test.mat = model.matrix(log(crim) ~ .,data = Boston[test ,])

Next we can form the predictions, and compute the test MSE for each size i.

val.errors =rep(NA ,13)
for(i in 1:13){
coefi=coef(regfit.best ,id=i)
pred=test.mat[,names(coefi)]%*% coefi
val.errors[i]= mean(( Boston$crim[test]-pred)^2)
}
val.errors

The best subset model picked a model with all but one predictor. The only variable that did not make the cut was chas which is a dummy variable indicating whether the tract bounds the river or not. The MSE of this model is 94.47

Ridge Regression

I will now test this with ridge regression. Ridge resgression must meet the same assupmtions as a linear model (except for normality), so I will maintain my log transformed per capita crime rate. I will first fit a ridge regression model:

library (glmnet)
## Warning: package 'glmnet' was built under R version 3.6.3
## Loading required package: Matrix
## Loaded glmnet 4.0
grid = 10^seq(10,-2, length =100)
ridge.mod = glmnet(Boston.pred, Boston.resp ,alpha = 0, lambda = grid)

Now, I can split my model into a training set and test set:

set.seed(1)
train.ridge = sample (1: nrow(Boston.pred), nrow(Boston.pred)/2)
test.ridge =(-train.ridge)
Boston.resp.test.ridge = Boston.resp[test.ridge]

Here, I use cross-validation to choose my tuning parameter, lambda:

set.seed (1)
cv.out =cv.glmnet (Boston.pred[train.ridge ,],Boston.resp[train.ridge],alpha =0)
plot(cv.out)

bestlam =cv.out$lambda.min
bestlam
## [1] 0.189988

Now I can fit my model with that tuning parameter:

ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod, s=bestlam, newx = Boston.pred[test.ridge ,])
mean((ridge.pred -Boston.resp.test.ridge)^2)
## [1] 0.5914915
out = glmnet(Boston.pred, Boston.resp, alpha =0)
predict (out ,type = "coefficients", s=bestlam )[1:14 ,]
##  (Intercept)           zn        indus         chas          nox           rm 
## -4.046773272 -0.010283794  0.014446929  0.018866537  3.448215643 -0.019571860 
##          age          dis          rad          tax      ptratio        black 
##  0.005849791 -0.044220291  0.101907245  0.001630171 -0.020010237 -0.001691092 
##        lstat         medv 
##  0.029607277  0.006974685

The ridge regression picked all variables (because it doesnt eliminate variables) with an MSE of 0.64. This is significantly better than the model selected by best subset selection. Next, I will use a Lasso Regression.

Lasso

First, I will fit the lasso model:

lasso.mod = glmnet(Boston.pred[train.ridge ,], Boston.resp[train.ridge],alpha =1, lambda =grid)
plot(lasso.mod)
## Warning in regularize.values(x, y, ties, missing(ties)): collapsing to unique
## 'x' values

Next, I will use the already created training and test sets and choose the best tuning parameter, lambda:

set.seed (1)
lasso.cv.out = cv.glmnet (Boston.pred[train.ridge ,], Boston.resp[train.ridge],alpha =1)
plot(lasso.cv.out)

bestlam.lasso = lasso.cv.out$lambda.min
lasso.pred = predict(lasso.mod ,s=bestlam.lasso ,newx=Boston.pred[test.ridge ,])
mean((lasso.pred -Boston.resp.test.ridge)^2)
## [1] 0.6059203

And here is my model:

out.lasso=glmnet(Boston.pred, Boston.resp,alpha =1, lambda =grid)
lasso.coef=predict(out.lasso, type = "coefficients", s=bestlam.lasso )[1:14 ,]
lasso.coef

You can see in this model, that all variables are maintained except for tax and chas. The MSE is 0.67. The MSE is just barely worse than the MSE for the ridge regression.

CONCLUSION

In order to predict per capita crime rate, we require a reliable model. After comparing a linear model selected with best subset selection, a ridge regression model, and a lasso model based on Mean Standard Error, I have selected both the ridge regression model and the lasso models. With MSEs of 0.64 and 0.67 respectively, they are not different enough to equivocally state that one is better than the other.
